  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Samuel Joseph May writes: &quot;On the 1st day of the year, we had a grand meeting of our cold weather Army in my meeting house.&quot; About twelve youths had temperance pieces that they presented. Samuel J. May is thinking of arranging a similar celebration in the interest of the anti-slavery cause, and for this he needs the help of Maria Weston Chapman and her sisters. He explains jokingly: &quot;And as you have nothing else to do I feel of course, no hesitation in calling upon you.&quot; He especially wants assistance devising suitable decorations.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Written in pencil below Samuel Joseph May&apos;s signature on page two of this manuscript, is the question: &quot;What say you?&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
